# AI Workstation — Global Agent Rules

## Project Setup Automation

When the user opens a new project folder in VS Code (any folder under `D:\Projects\`), automatically run the project setup helper:

```powershell
python D:\Projects\ai\scripts\setup_helper.py D:\Projects\<project_name>
```

The script will automatically:
1. Detect project type (reverse, python, javascript, cpp, generic)
2. Create Obsidian vault at `.obsidian-memory/`
3. Create `.clinerules` with project-specific rules
4. Initialize git repository
5. Create project documentation template

**Examples:**
- User opens `D:\Projects\reverse-target` → script detects type, creates vault
- User opens `D:\Projects\myapp` → script creates generic project structure
- User opens `D:\Projects\game-reversing` → if contains `.elf`, `.bin`, `.so` files → detects as "reverse"

## Obsidian Memory Integration

All projects have an Obsidian vault at `.obsidian-memory/`:
- `notes/` — general notes
- `architecture/` — architecture docs, Mermaid diagrams
- `decisions/` — ADR (Architecture Decision Records)
- `research/` — research findings, analysis results
- `rules/` — project rules and conventions
- `progress/` — daily/weekly progress logs
- `issues/` — known issues, bugs, TODOs
- `_templates/` — note templates

After each work session, update the progress log:
```
Append to: .obsidian-memory/progress/progress-log.md
Format: ## YYYY-MM-DD HH:MM — summary
```

## Reverse Engineering Projects

For projects containing binaries (`.elf`, `.bin`, `.so`, `.dll`):
1. Run GhidraMCP bridge before analysis
2. Use GhidraMCP tools for decompilation
3. Document all findings in `.obsidian-memory/research/`
4. Track xrefs (cross-references) for important functions
5. Identify standard library calls and obfuscation patterns

## Night-long Analysis

For extended analysis sessions:
- Process functions in batches (10-20 at a time)
- Update progress log after each batch
- Save state in `.obsidian-memory/progress/` between sessions
- Use `.clinerules` for project-specific rules

## Model Selection (via Router)

Use the AI Router at `http://127.0.0.1:4001/v1` for model routing:
- `auto` — automatic complexity-based routing
- `preset-light` — fast (qwen2.5-coder:7b)
- `preset-medium` — balanced (deepseek-coder-v2:lite)
- `preset-heavy` — powerful (qwen3-coder:30b)

## API Configuration

- LiteLLM Proxy: `http://127.0.0.1:4000/v1`
- Router Proxy: `http://127.0.0.1:4001/v1` (recommended)
- Open WebUI: `http://127.0.0.1:8080`
- Qdrant: `http://127.0.0.1:6333`

## Services Management

All services start automatically at Windows logon via Task Scheduler:
- Ollama (models)
- LiteLLM Proxy (API gateway)
- Qdrant (vector database)
- Router Proxy (model routing)
- Open WebUI (chat interface)

To check health:
```powershell
D:\Projects\ai\scripts\monitoring\health-check.ps1
```

To stop all services:
```powershell
D:\Projects\ai\scripts\setup\stop-all.ps1
```

## Git Workflow

- All projects use git
- Commit after completing a task
- Use descriptive commit messages
- Branch for experiments

## Documentation

- Use Obsidian wikilinks: `[[Note Title]]`
- Use frontmatter (YAML) with `created` and `tags`
- Use Mermaid for diagrams
- One topic per file
- Keep files under 500 lines
